After some thought, my question is: if the system of procrastinators can function, then what exactly is going on?
Why do these people all have such a dark corner?
As a result, I discovered that there are actually two types of procrastination.
The examples I mentioned today, as mentioned above, all have deadlines.
When there is a deadline, the impact of procrastination is limited to a relatively short period because the panic monster will intervene.
However, for the second type of procrastination, it occurs in situations without deadlines.
For example, if you want to start your own business or pursue a career in the arts, there is no initial deadline because nothing will happen until you start working hard, without any driving force to keep things moving forward.
Besides career-related matters, those important things also do not have deadlines, such as visiting your family, exercising to maintain physical health, making efforts to improve romantic relationships, or leaving an unsatisfactory relationship.
If procrastinators only have one mechanism to do these difficult things, which is the panic monster, then the problem arises because in these situations without deadlines, the panic monster simply will not appear.
He doesn't have a need to wake up, so the consequences of procrastination are unlimited, they will only keep postponing indefinitely.
And this long-term procrastination, compared to the more interesting, short-term, deadline-based procrastination, is not as obvious and is not often discussed.
It usually quietly and subtly affects us.
It may be a source of a significant amount of long-term unhappiness and guilt.
I think this is the reason why those people send emails, the reason why they are in such a terrible situation.
Not because they are rushing for a project,
It is this long-term procrastination that makes them feel like sometimes they are just spectators in their own lives.
Their frustration is not because they cannot achieve their dreams; it is because they cannot even start pursuing their dreams.
